2022 was full of adventures and books and French fries and dates and hikes and camping and the beach and good friends and some writing wins and learning more and more about our little wild person

this year I will continue to be tender & earnest despite despite despite, I will hope in the face of turmoil & fascism, I will believe in the power of tiny changes, I will continue to choose joy despite despite despite, I will unlearn as much as I learn, I will notice & embrace the small gestures of love, the minute to minute, the pass-you-by moments. i will remind myself that I am at my best when I am cheering on others, that jealousy & envy are human but that I can combat them by stepping outside myself, by remembering there is space for us all here, in the midst of success & euphoria & sweetness. I will continue to get closer to myself, to what fills me up & enriches my life, to what gives me gender euphoria & what makes me feel excited to inhabit a body, however limited this body may be. i will refuse shame & its insidiousness. & I will make art I’m excited about, despite despite despite.

Whiteknuckling my way through award season trying to remind myself it is arbitrary etc. trying to sit with my disappointed feelings while still celebrating others & their success. I’ve always been a competitive person & maybe that served me in sports but it feels inherently antithetical to creativity & making art, to channeling the humanity of it all. i don’t know, I don’t have it all figured out but trying to give myself grace while also pushing myself toward community & generosity, not envy or resentment. it feels both that this life is too short & this career is very long (if I’m lucky). Nothin to do but keep makin the shit i like & connect w the artists I admire, & fortunately, that’s so many of you.

Sign up through the link in my bio. A scholarship spot is available!

Blackouts by Justin Torres is all the best things: fuckin brilliant, very gay, experimental, sexy, sad, tender, & political. A story about queer erasure. A story within a story. A story about race and class and friendship and lost artifacts and memory. About who is pathologized and why. It reads like a holy text. And it’s going to linger for a long long time.
